INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '684fdc0c-81a3-4d21-b6bf-7a9908123a46',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elasticsearch TSDS — TimescaleDB Concepts Mapped to Native ES Time-Series$escape$,
  $escape$TimescaleDB's hypertable auto-partitions by time under the hood. Elasticsearch's equivalent is a Time Series Data Stream (TSDS), GA since 8.7. Set `index.mode: time_series` on your index template and declare a `routing_path` — your dimension fields like `host.name` or `service.name`. ES hashes these into a `_tsid` and co-locates all points for a given series on the same shard, giving you the same read locality that TimescaleDB guarantees per chunk.

For continuous aggregates, reach for ES Transforms: schedule a `date_histogram` + metric pivot on your TSDS index and materialize results into a rollup index. Dashboard queries hit the rollup — not the raw stream.

TSDSs apply a synthetic `_source` that physically stores metrics in a columnar layout automatically — no `best_compression` codec wrangling. Pair with ILM cold/frozen tiers to replicate TimescaleDB's `compress_after` and `drop_after` retention policies.

`time_bucket('1 hour', time)` maps directly to a `date_histogram` with `calendar_interval: 1h`. The mental model transfers cleanly once you know which ES primitive owns each TimescaleDB concept.$escape$,
  $escape$PUT _index_template/metrics-tsds
{
  "index_patterns": ["metrics-*"],
  "data_stream": {},
  "template": {
    "settings": {
      "index.mode": "time_series",
      "index.routing_path": ["host.name", "service.name"]
    },
    "mappings": {
      "properties": {
        "@timestamp":   { "type": "date" },
        "host.name":    { "type": "keyword", "time_series_dimension": true },
        "service.name": { "type": "keyword", "time_series_dimension": true },
        "cpu.pct":      { "type": "float",   "time_series_metric": "gauge" }
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
