INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '84628153-254b-4bb7-9c99-7d0c83d1d3ab',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elasticsearch Indexing Strategy — Inverted Index, BKD Trees, doc_values, and When to Disable Them$escape$,
  $escape$Elasticsearch uses different internal index structures depending on field type. Text fields build an inverted index — token → doc list — optimized for full-text search. Numeric, date, and geo fields use BKD trees (block k-d trees), which make range queries and geo-distance filters fast without scanning all docs.

For aggregations and sorting, Elasticsearch relies on doc_values — a columnar on-disk structure built at index time for keyword, numeric, and date fields. It's the equivalent of a covering index: data is pre-organized for retrieval without fetching _source. Disabling doc_values saves disk but kills sort/agg on that field.

Set index: false on fields you store but never query (e.g. raw payload blobs). Set doc_values: false on high-cardinality text fields used only for search. For text fields needing aggregations, avoid fielddata: true — it loads the entire uninverted index into heap. Instead, use a keyword sub-field.

Index sorting (index.sort.field) physically orders segments by a field, making early termination possible on top-N queries — analogous to a BRIN-style range optimization.$escape$,
  $escape$PUT /articles
{
  "settings": {
    "index.sort.field": "published_at",
    "index.sort.order": "desc"
  },
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "title": {
        "type": "text",
        "fields": { "keyword": { "type": "keyword", "doc_values": true } }
      },
      "view_count": { "type": "integer" },
      "raw_html":  { "type": "keyword", "index": false, "doc_values": false },
      "published_at": { "type": "date" }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
