INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b3d2e54e-34aa-4dbb-83fa-e4a711dc5997',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elasticsearch Concurrency — Optimistic Locking with _seq_no and _primary_term$escape$,
  $escape$Elasticsearch has no multi-document transactions or SQL isolation levels — writes are atomic only at the single-document level. For concurrent writes, it uses optimistic concurrency control via `_seq_no` and `_primary_term`. Every document carries these values; pass them as `if_seq_no` and `if_primary_term` on index, update, or delete requests. If another write modified the document since your read, Elasticsearch returns a `409 VersionConflictEngineException` — re-fetch and retry.

Pessimistic locking doesn't exist. There's no `SELECT FOR UPDATE` equivalent. The only pattern is: read → modify → write with version params → handle 409. For high-contention documents, implement retry logic with exponential backoff.

The old `_version` field (ES ≤ 6) is deprecated — always use `_seq_no` + `_primary_term`, which are shard-level monotonic counters reliable across distributed primaries.

One critical gotcha: `GET /<index>/_doc/<id>` is read-your-writes consistent (reads from the translog), but `POST /<index>/_search` only reflects the last segment refresh (1s default). A successful write is not immediately searchable.$escape$,
  $escape$# 1. Read the document to capture current seq_no and primary_term
GET /products/_doc/42
# Response includes: "_seq_no": 5, "_primary_term": 1

# 2. Conditionally update — 409 if document was modified since read
POST /products/_update/42?if_seq_no=5&if_primary_term=1
{
  "doc": { "stock": 99 }
}

# 3. On 409 VersionConflictEngineException:
#    Re-fetch document, re-apply your change, retry with new seq_no$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
