INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9c4c15b3-82f3-4cdd-962f-6839ab1c05cf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elasticsearch Sharding — Routing Keys, Hot Spots, and Partition Count$escape$,
  $escape$Elasticsearch routes every document to a shard using: `shard = hash(_routing) % number_of_primary_shards`. By default, `_routing` equals `_id`, giving even distribution but no data locality — queries fan out to all shards.

Custom routing groups related documents together. Index a log with `?routing=tenant-42` and all queries filtered by that tenant hit a single shard. Fast. But with only 3 high-traffic tenants across 10 shards, 7 shards sit idle while 3 get hammered — a classic hot spot.

`index.routing_partition_count` (must be < `number_of_shards`) spreads each routing key across a partition subset instead of one shard. With `routing_partition_count: 3`, `tenant-42` maps to 3 shards, not 1 — balancing locality with distribution. The mapping must mark `_routing` as required or the partition math breaks silently.

Diagnose hot spots with `GET /_cat/shards?v&h=shard,docs,store&s=store:desc`. Healthy clusters show roughly equal doc counts per shard; severe skew causes uneven query latency and OOM risk on the hot node.

Never change `number_of_shards` post-creation — it invalidates all routing calculations. Size correctly upfront and use the Rollover API with ILM for time-series indices.$escape$,
  $escape$PUT /logs
{
  "settings": {
    "number_of_shards": 10,
    "index.routing_partition_count": 3
  },
  "mappings": {
    "_routing": { "required": true }
  }
}

POST /logs/_doc?routing=tenant-42
{ "message": "Payment processed", "tenant_id": "tenant-42" }

GET /_cat/shards/logs?v&h=shard,docs,store&s=store:desc$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
